George Kerevan: Divided Europe gives Scots a choice
Another day, another spooky story about independence.
This time, there is a warning that a condition for an independent Scotland to join the EU would be its entry into Schengen.
This gave rise to tales of belt checks at Berwick and barbed wire along Hadrian's Wave.
The truth is that Strathclyde newspapers mentioned the possible economic benefits of free movement with the rest of Europe, but – as might be expected – this was not reflected in the headlines.
No one has also mentioned that EU Member States spend a lot of time adapting their official laws if it suits them.
Given that Scotland is not in Schengen now, the offer of continuing non-compliance would be a cheap concession for Brussels in return for whatever they really want from the Scots.
So it's a pretty weak story.
And also so old that it became an excavation. A journalist duck that "independence means passport control," I heard at least 40 years ago.
Still, there is one interesting idea hidden in this bearded tale.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to listen to Europe?
Why should we trade the London cumnut for the Brussels cumnut, especially now?
This is a true European story: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally failed.
As a result of the euro crisis, the so-called Project Europe is officially dead.
Across Europe, parties dedicated to resistance to the EU or the abolition of the euro as a common currency are gaining influence.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party – founded this year – came out of nowhere and had already won nearly five million votes in the September federal elections, essentially “throwing” the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberals) out of the Bundestag.
On domestic soil there has always been opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has become a decisive moment.
The austerity dictated by Germany and the European Central Bank, along with the tight-knit Kazakhs clinging to the national economies by sticking to the common currency, has led many people to believe that the project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with the fact that national governments are running a high budget deficit – this was true only in the case of Greece.
Rather, it is a system of the euro that blocks its members at exchange rates favourable to German exporters – and that is what German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluing the domestic currency, southern Europe has a disadvantage in terms of domestic production compared to Germany.
The only way to do this is to cut revenues and public spending, which Germany is encouraging.
With the current problems with the budget and currency, Europe's poor performance is a deeper cause.
As a result of the “green” energy policy supported by Brussels – a code to support French and German companies at the expense of consumers – European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gasoline as it does in the United States.
This is a paralyzing cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in the case of Grangemouth.
Even all the freezing of wages in the world would not deter the stifling of Europe’s petrochemical industry with cheap shale oil from the US.
The result is a simmering uprising, especially in France, once an enthusiastic supporter of the EU.
After the war, the political elite in France saw the EU as a tool that would keep Germany in check and allow Paris to rise to the level of Washington in the world.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a sign of political legitimacy, and has enforced its own economic policy in Europe, leaving the worn-out French economy to its fate.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s right wing, the anti-European National Front, has just won crucial by-elections and pushed the ruling socialists to third place.
The Front is now, with 24% of the vote, the most popular party in France – an early warning to British Labour that they cannot judge that the split of the right will automatically manifest itself positively on the left.
How does Le Pen cope with her newly gained popularity among the white working class?
She would like to use next year's European elections to create an anti-European bloc across the European Parliament against the single currency.
If the anti-European parties do well in these elections, which is likely, such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament for the first time in history.
In the foreseeable future, the growing anti-European sentiment and attitude towards the single currency will unite and destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but rather will turn into something more free in the sense of “Europe (sovereign) nations”, which General de Gaulle preferred.
Germany and several of its satellite economies may keep the euro, but France and southern Europe will renew their own currencies.
I expect the UK to distance itself from this project and close itself to the United States.
However, Washington’s increased interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left to the Atlantic cold.
Where will Scotland be?
We can choose to be an area (in principle) of Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – this includes the possibility of notifying Berlin and Brussels when they should leave us.
I assume that Scotland would do well in a relaxed Europe, provided that it retains its own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries would be easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should take the example of Norway and keep our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – oddly enough – the most successful political movement not promoting austerity in Europe, which won a large majority in 2011 thanks to an opposition stance against cuts planned (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor Alistair Darling and the following coalition of conservatives and libertarians.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to vote for independence now just to take austerity measures dictated by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: Adults earlier
Research has shown that African-Americans and Hispanics reach puberty earlier than their white peers.
Physical changes do not mean that puberty is approaching
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are behind this.
Experts claim that one of the triggers of earlier puberty may be an epidemic of obesity.
The trend of earlier puberty is not so evident in boys.
Former CNN reporter Pat Etheridge is a journalist who specializes in children’s health and family issues.
Should a mother be scared when her daughters start growing breasts and shaved at the age of 7 or 8?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatricians this week in Orlando, Florida, paediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent a new standard.
“I spent a lot of time reassuring my parents that this is usually not a sign of rapid development towards full puberty,” Kaplowitz said.
Visible signs of development, such as breast growth, hair loss on shame and in the armpits and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
For the past 40 years, however, there has been only a small shift in the age at which the first menstruation occurs.
In the United States, the average age is now 12.5 years compared to 12.75 years in 1970.
“When breasts begin to develop, it will be at least two to three years before the first menstruation occurs,” said Kaplowitz, who is also the author of the book “Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem” (Early Puberty in Girls: A Necessary Guide to Coping with This Common Problem).
The most reliable test of how puberty will continue is time.
It is discussed what triggers the actual onset of puberty, but if breast growth is accompanied by growth spurt before age 8, the girl is considered "premature".
In most cases, the process slows down or stops – which can be closely monitored by pediatricians.
Faster growth may be the reason for an endocrinologist to perform tests to rule out serious problems such as a tumor or cyst.
There are therapeutic procedures that delay early menstruation and prevent further consequences: premature aging of the bones, which can eventually lead to a halt to growth and decay in adulthood.
Recommendations regarding drugs and hormonal treatment depend on the age of the child, the speed of development, the speed of growth and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
When it comes to drug use, Kaplowitz is cautious, but acknowledges that “repressing puberty can alleviate problems with a girl’s behavior and her feelings of being different from her peers.”
Another big problem is understandable: Parents simply do not want their very young daughters to have menstruation.
"They're worried she might get pregnant, or how she'll handle hygiene," Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls a woman whose daughter began menstruating at the age of 10.
Although there were indications and we talked about menstruation together, she was not emotionally ready.
She came home from school scared and angry that she was the first of her friends.
There are many well-known theories about the causes of premature puberty.
However, there is still no consistent set of evidence that hormones are to blame in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz argues that the most serious reason is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped carry out a study on girls between the ages of 6 and 9, which associates body fat with the timing of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-Americans and Hispanics tend to reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts.
The explanations are different.
Globally, the patterns of early puberty seem to be affected by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another riddle: Although hair on the face and shame appear in boys at a young age, the trend towards full flowering of early puberty is not as evident as it is in girls.
Other physicians attending the American Association of Pediatricians (AAP) conference added additional complexity to this topic.
Acne and hair loss is common even in infants and toddlers.
“We need to be careful about how we identify the actual onset of puberty,” said Lawrence Silverman, a paediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to get instructions from their child's doctor on how to talk to their child.
“It may mean having to talk to a child before you know it,” said Kaplowitz.
If you stay calm, your child will probably respond well.
Girls who develop earlier need reassurance that even if this happens prematurely, this process is a common part of life.
