New Nicotine Vaccine May Take Away The Pleasure Of Smoking
Scientists have developed a nicotine vaccine that can take away the pleasure of smoking a cigarette.
A single dose of the vaccine was able to protect the mouse from nicotine dependence for a lifetime.
Before testing on humans, additional tests need to be done, which will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of the Weill Cornell School of Health in New York says the first signs are good.
“We strongly hope that this kind of vaccination strategy can finally help millions of smokers who have tried to stop and exhaust all the methods available on the market today, but have found that their nicotine dependence is so strong that it surpasses all current approaches,” said Professor Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been designed to carry genetic information to produce anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then begin to form a flow of these antibodies.
Antibodies chase all the nicotine molecules in the bloodstream and neutralize them before they get into the brain, preventing the smoker from getting a nicotine attack.
Vaccinated mice, who were given nicotine in addition, continued their normal activities.
But the mice that were not vaccinated “calmed down,” the researchers said, which is a sign that nicotine had gotten into their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
The injections had to be given so often to maintain sufficient levels of antibodies, so they proved to be expensive and impractical.
The cost of a new vaccine should be much lower, as it turns liver cells into factories for the production of antibodies.
Professor Crystal said that if future vaccines are completely safe for humans, they could be given to children before they feel like trying a cigarette, thus preventing nicotine addiction.
