But when she recorded the shooting of the tail mostly to the left (again from the sight of the dog whirling with the tail), their heart rate increased and the animals seemed uncertain.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think dogs would consciously communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, it is believed that dogs have learned from experience what movements they must and do not have to pay attention to.
He said, "If you meet dogs several times and the movement of their tail in one direction is repeatedly associated with rather friendly behavior and the movement to the right produces less friendly behavior, you will react based on this experience."
The researchers say the findings can help dog owners, veterinarians, and trainers better understand the emotions of their animals.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a university professor of veterinary medicine at the University of Bristol, said it was not the first study to examine whether the left and right sides are important for dogs.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they watch an aggressive dog, and to the right when they watch a cheerful dog.
And in another paper from the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: “Dogs were more likely to be introduced to the dog robot when he was spinning his tail to the left than to the right when they were becoming insecure — quite the opposite of an Italian study.”
The difference, he said, may be that dogs in these different studies did not interpret the animals in the movies or the dog robots quite like dogs.
He explained that studies on how dogs react to real dogs could help.
“Although there is strong evidence in many different mammals that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified – and dogs are no exception,” he said.
But given how easy it is to record their behavior, it probably won’t be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side and sometimes to the other.
