Egypt Appoints First Freely Elected President
Muhammad Mursi took the inaugural oath, but his triumphant day hardly ends the political unrest in Egypt.
ISLAMIST Muhammad Mursi promised a “new Egypt” when he was solemnly sworn in as the country’s first freely elected president, after Husni Mubarak, who had been deposed 16 months earlier.
When he was put in office before the Supreme Constitutional Court, Mursi also became the first freely elected Islamic president in the Arab world and the fifth Egyptian head of state since the overthrow of the monarchy some 60 years ago.
He took an oath before 18 judges dressed in black talars in a mansion built overlooking the Nile, which resembles an ancient Egyptian temple.
"We are striving for a better tomorrow, a new Egypt and a second republic," Mursi said at a ceremony broadcast live on state television.
“The Egyptian people today have laid the foundations of a new life – absolute freedom, true democracy and stability,” said Mursi, a 60-year-old U.S.-educated engineer and member of the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group that has been the target of fierce attacks by individual governments for most of the 84 years since its inception as an illegal organization.
When Mursi arrived shortly after 11 a.m. local time in a small column of cars, hundreds of soldiers and police guarded the building.
Only a few hundred supporters gathered in front of the courthouse to celebrate the president, and unlike Mubarak’s presidential glamor, traffic was briefly halted so that the column could traverse the usually busy road connecting the city centre with suburbs in the south.
Mursi’s personal prestige, mockingly referred to as the Muslim Brotherhood’s uncharismatic “reserving tire,” has grown sharply since his victory and Friday’s speech aimed at presenting him not only as a candidate for the Islamists, but also all those who want to bring the Mumu’s uprising to an end.
"Egypt today is a civil, national, constitutional and modern state," Mursi, dressed in a blue social suit with a red tie, told judges in a wood-lined chamber where he took an oath.
Mursi later traveled to the University of Cairo, where he was to deliver an inaugural speech.
While he stood on guard, he received an official welcome from the military band that played the national anthem.
Military commander Field Marshal Husayn Tantavi was present.
His arrival was accompanied by chanting “the army and the people are one hand” from the mouths of hundreds of people gathered in the university’s main lecture hall.
The University of Cairo was founded in 1908 as a center of secular education and later became a bastion of Islamic student movements in the 1970s.
Mursi took a symbolic oath on Friday at Tahrir Square, the birthplace of the revolution that ended Mubarak’s authoritarian rule last year, and solemnly promised to seize the presidential powers taken from his office by the military council, which took them from him.
But by agreeing to take an official oath before the court, rather than before parliament, as is customary, he submitted to the will of the army, suggesting that the struggle for power will continue.
Mursi’s speech on Tahrir Square was full of dramatic populist gestures.
