The coal mountain is the remnant of a young volcano.
Although data from radiometric age measurements vary somewhat, the last eruption here was about 1.5 million years ago.
It is therefore younger than the Great Red Riding Hood (3.3 million years old) and older than Venus's volcano (0.8 million years old).
The volcano was born by an explosion.
She threw out a considerable amount of volcanic ash along with fragments of rock from the substrate, which by burning obtained a reddish-brown color.
