Dr. Georges Bwelle provides free medical care in villages in Cameroon.
Bwelle and his team treat hundreds of patients almost every weekend
There are not too many doctors in West Africa; only one in 5,000.
Vote here or through your mobile phone.
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 candidates for the 2013 CNN Hero of the Year award.
In the 2013 CNN Hero of the Year contest, you can vote for him or any of the top ten candidates.
The winner will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years Georges Bwell has watched his father fall unconscious again and again and go to hospitals that were not equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near the Cameroonian capital Yaounde in 1981.
At first, he was treated only with a broken arm, but then he developed an infection that spread to the brain and there created a hematoma that caused him problems throughout his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” says Georges Bwelle.
We'd have to take him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwell spent years transporting his father to overcrowded clinics and hospitals, where he received treatment that was simply available.
"It's not easy," Bwell said.
You can leave the house at five in the morning, rush to the hospital to be there first, but you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people die just because they have to wait.
Since the death of Bwell's father in 2002, the situation has not changed much.
According to the World Health Organization, there is only one doctor per 5,000 inhabitants in Cameroon.
Just for comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor per 413 population.
And even if doctors could visit Cameroonians, many would not be able to afford it.
Two out of five people in this country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of health care spending in this country is private.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” says Bwelle.
Because of poverty, they can't enjoy life.
When Bwell saw his father and many of his countrymen suffering, he decided to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwell and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries last year.
He became a vascular surgeon at Yaounde Central Hospital.
And he founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, whose members visit rural areas on the weekends, where they provide medical care for free.
Since 2008, he has helped nearly 32,000 people with his group of volunteers.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people rush into supplies, attach medical supplies to rooftops, and travel through rough terrain to villages in need of help.
It is not always accompanied by happiness.
Sometimes vehicles have to push through the river and mud.
But when they arrive, they are greeted as true heroes: feasting, singing and dancing, and the best accommodation the community has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is truly a reason to celebrate, and Bwell – with his broad smile and unbridled energy – is very willing to engage in local fun.
The next day, the team begins to treat hundreds of patients.
“We have 500 patients on each trip,” says Bwelle.
They come to the village from a 60-kilometer radius, on foot.
During each of these weekends, doctors provide a variety of medical assistance.
Many are treated with malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasitic diseases and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others can get bells or gifted glasses or a birth certificate for free – a document that the school requires but that many impoverished families simply cannot afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations under local anesthesia.
Surgery is usually done in the school building, in the city hall or at home; after surgery, the patient gets up and goes to the recovery site to free up space for another patient.
With the help of light from the generator, operating room and hygienic equipment, Bwell and his volunteers work until early in the morning.
It’s exhausting, but village musicians usually help the team not to lose motivation.
“To stay up and keep working, they’re playing drums all night,” says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team will head back to town, tired but proud of their work.
This group – consisting of Cameroonian physicians and international medical students – performed 700 free surgeries last year and realizes that their help can mean a lot to locals.
One man said that after the operation the hernia will be able to work again.
"That will change our family's future," the man said.
In addition to organizing these weekend clinics and the work of a surgeon at Bwelle Hospital, he also works at night for private health clinics around the city of Yaounde.
He says that this second work finances about 60% of his non-profit activities; the rest cover private contributions.
“I’m not sure when he’s actually sleeping,” says Katie O’Malley, who has been studying medicine for the second year at Drexel University in Philadelphia and is working as a volunteer for the Bwelle group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to get money for the organization to do these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O’Malley who came from the United States or Europe to join Bwelle on his mission, it’s a great practice they wouldn’t get at home.
“We thoroughly washed Dr. Bwell’s hands and removed blood stains or held his instruments,” says O’Malley.
As a medical student in your second year in America, you will never experience this.
Student volunteers usually pay for their trip to Cameroon on their own and often arrive with donated medical needs.
But once they arrive in Yaounde, Bwelle provides them with food, transportation and study.
"He's definitely a hero," says O'Malley.
This organization gives its life and its desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
For Bwell, constant denial is not a burden.
Helping others live happier, fulfilling the promise he made to his father, is something that brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy to be doing this job,” Bwelle says.
And I mean my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
Laughing at people, alleviating their pain – that’s why I do it.
