How the Insects of Thailand Raised the Sales of the Paris Bar
You may grumble over an insect and have no idea that you are consuming about half a kilogram of it a year completely voluntarily.
For example, ground in flour.
If you consume it consciously, then you are definitely trendy: it is ecological, nutritious and you also have taken care of a unique experience.
He was the first person in Paris to list the insects on the menu of his company in early October by Elie Daviron, chef and owner of Le Festin Nu.
The bar, for which the name was inspired by William Burroughs’ book Naked Lunch, is located in the fashionable 18th arrondissement near Montmartre, which is heavily visited by tourists.
With fresh avocado, roasted red peppers, ginger and quail eggs, guests can taste not only different larvae, moths or water bugs, but also squirrels.
Carefully and specially packaged supplies (so that insects do not damage their wings, curl their legs or damage their eyes) are sent to Daviron from Thailand.
Europe is only learning to eat insects, elsewhere it is common.
The owner of the Paris bar with a pioneering menu immediately lists several reasons why to consume insects.
The first of these is the ecological benefit, because insect production is much less expensive for our planet (in terms of finance, space and water consumption) than traditional meat.
"In addition, insects are an excellent source of protein and omega 3 fatty acids," Daviron told Reuters.
At the same time, the young chef does not deny his profession, he simply aims to offer his customers a unique culinary experience.
According to him, it makes the right restaurant pleasure, a sense of sin and the atmosphere of the environment.
"I'm not saving the world, I'm just conveying a new experience," he explained.
Not everyone would be fascinated by the idea of eating a bug decorated with pests, but the reaction of the customers of the Paris bar to the served insects is very positive, according to the owner.
